I muſt profeſs my ſelf, though ſometimes in an haſte as prone to aculeate language as any man, yet upon conſideration to be naturally no friend unto Invectives, nor apt much to applaud their authours; it being an eaſie thing for any one almoſt to be eloquent againſt men, whoſe either vices croſs his Genius, or party thwarts his intereſt, and eaſieſt of all things to ſome, who have wits after a ſort framed thereto; of which kinde I have known many, that can never for their hearts compoſe any thing excellent, unleſs they have ſomewhat that they may throughly laſh at. Such perſons we may obſerve to be commonly full of 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 , humourſome, and much in love with themſelves and their own. The contemplation of their humour
